label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Council Chambers | Late Afternoon — Storm Clouds Gathering]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full, urgent strings — pulse like a rising tide]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain pattering against the windows; a distant foghorn a low, steady note]
    "You step forward from the cluster of volunteers and neighbors as Councilor Marco clears his throat. Your field notebook is closed in your hand; the brass compass at your throat is warm from your palm. Your"
    "cheeks sting from the cold and from the way the room watches you like a held breath."
    "Your pulse is a drumbeat under your collarbone. Every argument you've rehearsed—every map, every Polaroid, every small-bodied datum Asha insisted you carry out—arrives in sequence behind your ribs. This is not an abstract vote. This is"
    "Tomas's shop, Rosa's memories, the sound of nets on the pier. This is all of it pressed into a single exhale."
    show councilor_marco_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    councilor_marco_lin "We have heard testimony from all sides. The motion before us is a conditional approval for targeted, phased coastal protection—Aurelia's structure scaled down for immediate commercial zones—with binding requirements for adjacent living-shoreline modules, habitat restoration funds, and small-business resilience programs."
    "A rustle goes through the room like wind through reeds. June Park stands near the dais, expression unreadable; her team murmurs behind her, tablet screens cold and impassive. You don't need to look at them to know what they would prefer."
    show asha_malik at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_malik "Engineering without ecology solves a single storm and precipitates the next. Phased measures allow us to protect the immediate economic heart of San Brisa while layering in natural systems that reduce long-term risk. We can bind these requirements legally. We can monitor. We must."
    "Her voice is a rope—soft but unbreakable—and the room leans into it. You feel it: the legal language she speaks will outlast the speeches, outlast June's polished presentations. Asha translates salinity curves into consequences that fit"
    "into people's daily images—Tomas's door swollen and stuck, Rosa's garden soil washed into the bay. You watch faces soften."
    show rosa_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "When my mother taught me to roast fish over coals, she did it on that boardwalk. It was crooked and the screws were always loose—so what? We loved it. We fixed it, again and again. If you build only for profit and not for people, you will take the boardwalk and you will take the story with it."
    "There's a murmur—some laughter, some sobs—then a raw, unanimous quiet. The councilors look at each other; a human image is sometimes the strongest evidence of all."
    "You glance briefly at Tomas, sitting two rows back. He meets your eyes and gives you a small, lopsided smile that says: I'm scared, but I know who I am. He has chosen the relocation-aid path"
    "that will let his shop survive—smaller, yes, but alive in another form. The ache behind your ribs loosens into something like resolve."

    councilor_marco_lin "This council recognizes both the urgency and the uncertainty. We will move with a phased approach—protecting commerce now, mandating living modules adjacent to the structure, creating an escrow for habitat restoration, and establishing a grant for displaced small businesses."
    "The chamber holds its breath. The clerk reads the motion again, each phrase like a tightening knot being worked free."

    menu:
        "Raise your fist with the crowd":
            "You lift your arm; the gesture quickens the chant outside. It is small and public and furious in the best way."
        "Remain still, letting the moment settle":
            "You keep your hands at your sides and let the sound of the decision wash over you, cataloguing each face in the room like a new map."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues."
    "Councilor Marco counts the votes. His voice is ironically calm for what it carries."

    councilor_marco_lin "All those in favor—"
    "You taste salt in the air, a mix of rain and the shuttle of many lives converging. The first 'aye' is a single, bright note. Then another. The sound grows, an accelerating wave. When he reaches"
    "the 'nays,' they are small, tight, dignified. June's team registers theirs with engineering precision; they will take what they can and fight from where they can."
    "A hush follows the gavel. Marco's hand comes down."

    councilor_marco_lin "Motion passes with conditions."
    "A sound you did not know you had held—the sound of your own breath catching—escapes in a laugh that breaks into something like crying. Around you, people exhale in a collective release that rattles the room."
    "Someone begins to clap; it spreads like rolling surf. Asha's smile is brief and fierce. Rosa wipes her eyes with the back of her hand and laughs, a high, disbelieving sound. Tomas stands and joins the"
    "crowd, slapping a neighbor's shoulder as if to say: We are still here."
    hide councilor_marco_lin
    show june_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    june_park "You made good arguments, Ms. Reyes. Binding language. You found the coalition. You have leverage."
    "You want to say a dozen things—the moral of ecosystems, the future of the pier—but what comes out is simple."
    hide asha_malik
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We negotiated for the town. For people. Not just pylons."
    "June regards you for a long beat, then nods once, as if conceding a fact she cannot ignore."

    june_park "Then tend it. Hold them to it."
    "Her words are a charge and a threat folded into the same neat sentence. You hear the echo of her childhood fear—how quickly planners can erase people in the name of safety. You accept the charge like a hot coal; it burns, but it is real."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain heightens to a curtain; voices outside coalesce into cheers and the distant beat of drums.]
    "You leave the chamber with the crowd pushing like a tide towards the street. Cameras flash; strangers clasp hands. The mood is raw and ringing, hope braided with exhaustion. You feel Eli at your shoulder before"
    "you see him, his presence a warm steady hand on the small of your back."
    hide rosa_alvarez
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You did it. You did the thing that makes other things possible."

    maya_reyes "We did it. All of us."
    "Your eyes find Tomas in the crowd—he's talking to Rosa, already making lists on a napkin. Plans are beginning, already messy and human. This is not victory in the way of banners and complete certainty; it is a scaffolding around which a future can be grown."
    hide june_park
    hide maya_reyes
    hide eli_navarro

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells into a triumphant brass and string convergence — then softens into hopeful piano]
    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden | Night — Amber Bulbs, Humid Air]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Night market chatter, occasional laughter, the clink of glasses]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, intimate acoustic guitar with a steady heartbeat rhythm]
    "You climb the narrow metal stair with Eli at your side. The rooftop smells of wet soil, grilled fish from the stalls below, and something like repair—fresh-cut wood and old rope. Your hands are damp from"
    "the leaf-grease of thumb-rolled petitions, but in your pocket the Polaroid of the barge feels like a talisman."
    "Eli Navarro kneels at a trough of seedlings, his fingers working the soil—clay under his nails, the faint, honest smell of earth. He looks up when you arrive, and his grin is the kind that rearranges your chest."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "Your hands smell like policy and rain. Mine smell like clay. Together we smell like a plan."
    "You both laugh. The joke is small, a shared language of tactile work. There is something profound in naming the mundane; it means you are both anchored in the same, stubborn reality."
    "You sit on the edge of a planter and pull out a scrap of paper—the town's new conditional mandate, sketched with highlighted clauses and footnotes in Asha's handwriting. Eli unfolds his own—maps, a list of volunteer"
    "crews, a penciled prototype for modular living-shoreline frames he wants to test in the inlet."

    eli_navarro "We need monitoring teams. A public dashboard. Community-sourced sensors so people can see how the modules perform. And microgrants—minute, targeted funds to keep shops afloat while we build resilience."
    "You trace a line in the margin where 'escrow for habitat restoration' meets 'small business emergency fund.'"
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Asha will head the science team. Rosa will host monthly memory-mapping sessions so we never lose the stories that justify the work. Tomas will... consolidate, yes. But he'll open the satellite stall at the night market. He'll be a presence."

    eli_navarro "He'll still be there, Maya. He'll change form, but he won't be erased."
    "His certainty is a buoy. You let yourself be held by it for a moment—by the fact that someone can believe in the continuity of a small life even as the coastline redraws itself."

    menu:
        "Pull Eli close and celebrate with a kiss":
            "You do. It's brief and electric, a punctuation after a long sentence of tension and a promise that you are choosing each other while the town chooses itself."
        "Hold his hands and plan instead":
            "You take his hands in both of yours and lay out the steps—monitoring, outreach, community shifts. The touch is quiet, planning as intimacy."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues."
    "Eli leans back and looks at the low horizon, where the city's lights pulse against the cloud bank. He rubs soil from his palms and offers them to you to smell—a ridiculous, tender ritual."

    eli_navarro "We have to be patient. Not the waiting of helplessness, but patient like tide-watchers. We will check, re-check, fix, and guard. That will be our work together."
    "You breathe in the night: herb smoke, salt, the tinny music from the market. It hums against the brightness of the bulbs and makes the world feel small enough to touch and vast enough to matter."

    maya_reyes "We will be slow and stubborn. We'll make it boring to the powers that prefer fast profit. We'll make accountability a habit."

    eli_navarro "And we'll make a ridiculous playlist to go with our community monitoring shifts."
    "Your laughter threads between you, and for a moment the rooftop is a private island: two people and a map and a plan. The night's energy is pulsing—very high and alive—but it is a new kind of charge: collaborative, creative, guarded by the knowledge that consequence follows every move."
    "You both rise and walk the terrace, touching seedlings, imagining where each living module could anchor to shore. You draft names aloud—volunteer leads, neighbors to recruit, a public workshop series hosted by Rosa. Each named person makes the future more plausible."

    maya_reyes "This is not complete victory. Some streets will be lost, some doors will close. But the governance now binds ecology to policy. We have a mandate to enforce—finite, imperfect, and real."
    "Eli Navarro squeezes your hand, a silent oath."

    eli_navarro "We will guard it. You'll hold the science; I'll help build the frames and the human networks. We'll keep Tomas's stall in mind when we schedule the build days so he can keep selling his wares between shifts."
    "The two of you look at the night market below—lamps, faces, the resilient bustle of a town living despite weather and debt. It shines in patches, imperfect but warm."
    "You close your eyes and imagine the repaired pier board you loved as a child—one new plank there, another here. The memory is not unbroken, but the new boards hold. They creak in different places now,"
    "and you understand that repair is a craft, not a return. You feel a steady happiness, not the fireworks of total triumph but the deep, steady kind that comes from building something that will outlast the"
    "two of you."
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swelling strings resolve into a warm major chord; a single alto voice hums a lullaby motif]
    "You make a small, private promise—no grand declarations, just a vow to show up. To monitor. To protest if Aurelia's contractors slip the bindings. To seed living modules, to teach, to measure, to lend a hand"
    "when Tomas needs a plank. To love, in the small practical ways both of you understand."
    "You watch the mist roll over the edge of the harbor and then recede, revealing the distant lights like scattered bioluminescence. The town is not whole. Some doors will be relocated. Some memories will be trimmed"
    "and grafted into new rituals. But governance now holds a new line—a legal spine that names ecology and community as partners."
    "You rest your head against Eli's shoulder. The night market hums below, the rooftop plants drip in the mist, and the bulbs above cast an amber glow that makes everything a little softer, a little more forgiving."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We will watch the tide. We will be patient."
    show eli_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "Tide-watchers."
    "You both laugh softly, the sound small and durable in the dark."
    hide maya_reyes
    hide eli_navarro

    scene bg ch15_3be532_5 at full_bg
